jurisdictions.habitability_section:
A.R.S. § 33-1324. LANDLORD TO MAINTAIN FIT PREMISES.

A. The landlord shall:
1. Comply with requirements of applicable building codes materially affecting health and safety;
2. Make all repairs and do whatever is reasonably necessary to put and keep the premises in a fit and habitable condition;
3. Keep all common areas of the premises in a clean and safe condition;
4. Maintain in good and safe working order and condition all electrical, plumbing, sanitary, heating, ventilating, air-conditioning and other facilities and appliances, including elevators, supplied or required to be supplied by the landlord;
5. Provide and maintain appropriate receptacles necessary for the removal of ashes, garbage, rubbish and other waste incidental to the occupancy of the dwelling unit and arrange for their removal;
6. Supply running water and reasonable amounts of hot water at all times and reasonable heat and air conditioning or cooling where such units are installed and offered, when required by seasonal weather conditions, EXCEPT where: (a) the building where the dwelling unit is located is not required by law to be equipped with such facilities; or (b) the dwelling unit is so constructed that heat, air conditioning, cooling or hot water is generated by an installation within the exclusive control of the tenant and supplied by a direct public utility connection.

B. If the duty imposed by paragraph 1 of subsection A is greater than any duty imposed by any other paragraph, the landlord's duty shall be determined by paragraph 1 of subsection A.

C. [Single family home exception] The landlord and a tenant of a single family residence may agree in writing that the tenant perform specified repairs, maintenance tasks, alterations and remodeling, but only if: the agreement is entered into in good faith and not for the purpose of evading the obligations of the landlord; and the work is not necessary to cure noncompliance with paragraphs 1 and 2 of subsection A.

D. [Multi-unit limitation] For units other than single family: landlord and tenant may only agree for tenant to perform specified maintenance if: entered in good faith, separate writing, adequate consideration; not to cure paragraphs 1 and 2 violations; agreement does not diminish obligations to other tenants.

jurisdictions.eviction_section:
C.R.S. § 38-12-1303 (HB 1121, 2022). JUST CAUSE EVICTION PROTECTIONS.
(1) After 12 months of continuous residency, a landlord may not terminate a tenancy or fail to offer to renew a lease without 'just cause.'

(2) Just cause reasons include:
(a) Nonpayment of rent;
(b) Material violation of lease terms (with 10-day notice to cure);
(c) Holding over after proper notice;
(d) Substantial damage to premises;
(e) Criminal activity on premises;
(f) Owner/family member move-in (90-day notice required, owner must occupy ≥12 months);
(g) Substantial renovation requiring tenant vacancy (120-day notice; relocation assistance required);
(h) Conversion to non-residential use (120-day notice);
(i) Sale of property if buyer intends to occupy (90-day notice);
(j) Demolition (120-day notice);
(k) Conversion to short-term rental (90-day notice).

(3) No-fault evictions requiring relocation assistance: Landlord must provide one month's rent as relocation assistance when terminating for reasons (f)–(k) above.

Notice periods:
- Nonpayment: 10-day Demand for Compliance or Possession (C.R.S. §13-40-104(1)(d))
- Lease violation: 10-day Cure or Quit notice
- Month-to-month termination: 91 days' notice (as of HB 1098, 2024)

C.R.S. § 38-12-1302(b): Just cause protections do NOT apply if the owner or master tenant lives in the unit as primary residence or the unit is within a structure of 2 or fewer units AND owner occupies one.

jurisdictions.landlord_entry_section:
Colorado has no specific advance notice statute in Article 12 for landlord entry. However, C.R.S. § 38-12-503 (habitability) and lease terms govern. Courts apply common law standard of 'reasonable notice.'

Colorado industry standard and most lease agreements: 24-hour advance notice.

C.R.S. § 38-12-509. PROHIBITED RETALIATORY ACTS. A landlord shall not:
(a) Increase rent;
(b) Decrease services;
(c) Commence eviction;
(d) Threaten to evict; or
(e) Take any other retaliatory action
in response to a tenant who has: (1) reported housing code violations to government; (2) filed complaint with government agency; (3) exercised any rights under this part; or (4) organized or joined a tenant organization.

jurisdictions.habitability_section:
Fla. Stat. § 83.51. LANDLORD'S OBLIGATION TO MAINTAIN PREMISES.

(1) The landlord at all times during the tenancy shall:
(a) Comply with the requirements of applicable building, housing, and health codes; or
(b) Where there are no applicable building, housing, or health codes, maintain the roofs, windows, doors, floors, steps, porches, exterior walls, foundations, and all other structural components in good repair and capable of resisting normal forces and loads and the plumbing in reasonable working condition.

(2)(a) Unless otherwise agreed in writing, in addition to the requirements of subsection (1), the landlord of a dwelling unit other than a single-family home or duplex shall, as applicable, make reasonable provisions for:
1. The extermination of rats, mice, roaches, ants, wood-destroying organisms, and bedbugs. When vacation of the premises is required for such extermination, the landlord shall not be liable for damages but shall abate the rent. The landlord must provide reasonable notice of not less than 7 days with a written notice of the need to vacate for a period not to exceed 4 days;
2. Locks and keys;
3. The clean and safe condition of common areas;
4. Garbage removal and outside receptacles therefor;
5. Functioning facilities for heat during winter, running water, and hot water.
(b) Unless otherwise agreed in writing, at the commencement of the tenancy of a single-family home or duplex, the landlord shall install working smoke detection devices.

O.C.G.A. § 44-7-13. DUTY TO KEEP PREMISES IN REPAIR.
The landlord must keep the premises and all common areas in repair and may not permit dilapidation due to ordinary wear and tear. However, Georgia does NOT have a statutory implied warranty of habitability as robust as many other states.

Georgia courts have recognized an implied covenant of quiet enjoyment and habitability under common law: Ariemma v. Kash N' Karry Corp.

Practical standards: Georgia building codes and health codes impose minimum habitation standards. If a landlord allows premises to become uninhabitable, the tenant may:
1. Notify landlord in writing;
2. If not repaired within a reasonable time, tenant may repair and deduct (limited common law remedy);
3. Treat lease as constructively terminated (abandonment with potential rent credit);
4. Sue for damages.

Code enforcement: Local code enforcement agencies can order repairs to dangerous conditions.

jurisdictions.eviction_section:
ILLINOIS EVICTION NOTICE REQUIREMENTS:

735 ILCS 5/9-209. DEMAND FOR RENT. When rent is due and unpaid, the landlord may, before beginning a lawsuit for eviction, make a written demand requiring the tenant to pay the rent or surrender possession within 5 DAYS after service of the notice.

735 ILCS 5/9-210. OTHER LEASE VIOLATIONS. For violations other than nonpayment of rent, the landlord may serve a written notice specifying the nature of the violation and demanding remedy or surrender within 10 DAYS of service.

735 ILCS 5/9-207. HOLDOVER/MONTH-TO-MONTH TERMINATION.
For month-to-month tenancies: 30 days written notice from either party.

Illinois has NO statewide just cause eviction requirement. Landlord may choose not to renew at end of lease term.

CHICAGO RLTO §5-12-130 (2021 JUST CAUSE AMENDMENT):
For tenants who have resided in Chicago rental unit for 2+ years, landlord may not terminate lease or refuse to renew without just cause, including:
(a) Nonpayment of rent;
(b) Violation of material term of lease;
(c) Nuisance, illegal use;
(d) Owner or family member occupancy (120-day notice, 6 months of good-faith occupancy required);
(e) Building demolition or major renovation (120-day notice + relocation assistance = 3 months rent);
(f) Removal from rental market (120-day notice + relocation assistance = 3 months rent).

For tenants of <2 years in Chicago: Still requires proper notice; no-fault termination allowed.

jurisdictions.security_deposit_section:
N.C.G.S. § 42-50. DEPOSITS FROM THE TENANT.
Security deposits from the tenant in residential dwelling units shall be deposited in a trust account with a licensed and federally insured depository institution or a trust institution authorized to do business in North Carolina, to be held therein until the following disposition. The deposit shall not be commingled with the landlord's own funds. In lieu of a deposit trust account, a landlord with 10 or more residential rental units may keep a surety bond in the amount of the deposits held. The landlord shall provide written notice of the name of the depository where the tenant's deposit is held.

N.C.G.S. § 42-51. PERMITTED USES OF THE DEPOSIT.
(a) Damage deposits collected from a residential tenant may be applied only for the following purposes:
(1) The payment of accrued unpaid rent and other lawful charges due under the rental agreement;
(2) The payment of damages to the leased premises or dwelling unit that are not the result of ordinary wear and tear;
(3) Payment of court costs in connection with terminating a tenancy;
(4) Payment of any unpaid bills that become a lien against the leased property due to the tenant's occupancy;
(5) Payment of the costs of re-renting the premises after breach by the tenant;
(6) Payment of any fee agreed upon in the rental agreement;
(7) Compensation for the tenant's early termination of the rental agreement.

N.C.G.S. § 42-51(b). DEPOSIT CAPS.
(b) In the case of residential dwelling units, the following limitations apply:
(1) For month-to-month tenancy: not more than ONE AND ONE-HALF MONTH'S rent;
(2) For term tenancy (term >2 months): not more than TWO MONTHS' rent;
(3) For furnished units: additional reasonable deposit for furnishings.

N.C.G.S. § 42-52. LANDLORD'S OBLIGATIONS UPON TERMINATION OF TENANCY.
Upon termination of the tenancy, the landlord shall return the deposit or provide the tenant with an itemized accounting of deductions, together with the balance of the deposit, not later than 30 DAYS after the termination of the tenancy and the tenant's demand for return, or the provision of a forwarding address, whichever occurs last. If the landlord fails to comply, the landlord forfeits the right to retain any portion of the deposit and shall pay the tenant a sum equal to the deposit owed. Additionally, the landlord shall be liable for double (2x) the deposit amount wrongfully withheld if the failure to return was in bad faith.

N.C.G.S. § 42-53. COURT ACTION FOR RETURN OF DEPOSIT.
In addition to the remedies above, the tenant may recover additional damages in a court action. The court may award damages up to twice the amount wrongfully withheld.

jurisdictions.habitability_section:
N.C.G.S. § 42-42. LANDLORD'S OBLIGATIONS. IMPLIED WARRANTY OF HABITABILITY.
(a) The landlord shall:
(1) Comply with the current applicable building and housing codes, whether enacted before or after the effective date of this article;
(2) Make all repairs and do whatever is reasonably necessary to put and keep the premises in a fit and habitable condition;
(3) Keep all common areas of the premises in safe condition;
(4) Maintain in good and safe working order and promptly repair all electrical, plumbing, sanitary, heating, ventilating, air conditioning, and other facilities and appliances supplied or required to be supplied by the landlord provided that notification by the tenant of needed repairs is given;
(5) Provide operable smoke detectors, either battery-operated or electrical, having an Underwriters' Laboratories listing or equivalent national testing laboratory approval, and install the detectors in accordance with either the standards of the National Fire Protection Association or the minimum protection designated in the manufacturer's instructions, which the tenant shall maintain.

(b) The provisions of this section shall apply to all residential rental agreements in North Carolina. The obligations of the landlord under this section may not be waived. Any condition which is the result of the tenant's misconduct, negligence, or neglect does not constitute a breach by the landlord.

jurisdictions.eviction_section:
New York Real Property Law § 226-C. NOTICE OF RENT INCREASE OR NONRENEWAL.
(1) An owner who intends to offer a renewal of a lease or a rental agreement at an increased rent or who intends not to renew a lease or a tenancy at the expiration of such lease or tenancy shall provide written advance notice as follows:
(a) if the tenant has occupied the premises for less than one year, or if the tenant has a lease term of less than one year: not less than 30 days before the proposed effective date;
(b) if the tenant has occupied the premises for one year or more but less than two years, or has a lease term of at least one year but less than two years: not less than 60 days before the proposed effective date;
(c) if the tenant has occupied the premises for two or more years or has a lease term of two or more years: not less than 90 days before the proposed effective date.

N.Y. Real Property Law § 231-C. GOOD CAUSE EVICTION (2024 Statewide).
Effective April 20, 2024 (Part BB of FY25 Budget): Extends Good Cause Eviction protections statewide.
(a) Covered units: All residential rentals statewide EXCEPT: (1) units in buildings with ≤4 units AND owner lives in one unit; (2) units with rent above 245% of fair market rent; (3) condos/co-ops; (4) buildings built within past 30 years; (5) units subject to regulation under other laws (rent stabilization, etc.).
(b) Grounds for eviction: A landlord may not evict a tenant without 'good cause' including:
(1) Nonpayment of rent (with proper notice);
(2) Violation of substantial obligation of tenancy;
(3) Disorderly conduct;
(4) Willful damage;
(5) Illegal use;
(6) Refusal to allow access;
(7) Owner or immediate family member move-in;
(8) Withdrawal from rental market;
(9) Other enumerated reasons.
(c) Rent increase > 5% is presumed unreasonable and may constitute basis for eviction defense.

N.Y. Real Property Law § 232-A. NYC MONTH-TO-MONTH TERMINATION. No monthly tenancy or tenancy from month to month in the city of New York may be terminated except upon the giving of 30 days notice prior to the expiration of the term.

N.Y. Real Property Law § 232-B. OUTSIDE NYC. No monthly tenancy or tenancy from month to month outside of New York City may be terminated except upon the giving of one month's notice prior to the expiration of the term.

[Unlawful detainer/summary proceeding: Real Property Actions and Proceedings Law (RPAPL) Article 7 §§ 701-783 governs judicial eviction proceedings. 3-day notice for nonpayment of rent (RPAPL §711).]

jurisdictions.late_fees_section:
N.Y. Real Property Law § 238-A (HSTPA 2019). FEES PROHIBITED.
(1) A landlord of a residential dwelling may not:
(a) Charge a late fee before the fifth day after the date rent is due (5-day grace period STATEWIDE);
(b) The late fee may not exceed $50 or 5% of monthly rent, whichever is less;
(c) Charge any fee for accepting rent payment by personal check or electronic funds transfer.

jurisdictions.eviction_section:
RCW 59.18.650. JUST CAUSE EVICTION (Enacted 2021, amended 2022, 2023).
(1) A landlord may not evict a tenant, refuse to continue a tenancy, or end a periodic tenancy without cause. (Applies to all residential tenancies.)
(2) JUST CAUSE REASONS and notice periods:
(a) Nonpayment of rent – notice per RCW 59.12.030 (14-day Pay or Vacate);
(b) Material breach of lease terms – at least 10 days notice;
(c) Waste, nuisance, unlawful activity, serious disturbance – at least 3 days notice;
(d) Owner/immediate family member move-in – at least 90 days notice;
(e) Sale of single-family home to buyer intending to occupy – at least 90 days notice;
(f) Compliance with government agency order under RCW 59.18.200 – per that statute;
(g) Condominium conversion – per separate statutes;
(h) Premises condemned/unfit – at least 30 days notice;
(i) Owner shares kitchen or bath (owner-occupied housing) – at least 20 days notice;
(j) End of transitional housing program eligibility – at least 30 days notice;
(k) Refusal to sign new reasonable lease – at least 30 days notice;
(l) Material misrepresentation on application – at least 30 days notice;
(m) Valid business/economic reason (bona fide) – at least 60 days notice;
(n) Four or more lease violations in 12 months (each previously cured) – at least 60 days;
(o) Registered sex offender not disclosed – at least 60 days;
(p) Sexual harassment or protected-class-based harassment – at least 20 days.
(3) Fixed-term lease: At natural expiration of initial lease term of 6-12 months, landlord may non-renew without just cause with 60 days notice. After first renewal or if tenancy >12 months, just cause required.
(4) Violations: Landlord who violates this section liable for actual and non-economic damages, or 3x monthly rent, whichever is greater, plus attorney's fees.
(6) All notices must: be served per RCW 59.12.040; specify the facts supporting the just cause.

RCW 59.18.057. 14-DAY NOTICE FORMAT (Nonpayment).
Notice must contain: (1) amount of rent due; (2) statement of tenant rights; (3) list of legal aid resources; (4) AG website for tenant information; (5) statement about payment plans; (6) mediation resources.

jurisdictions.landlord_entry_section:
RCW 59.18.150. LANDLORD'S RIGHT OF ENTRY.
(1) The landlord shall not abuse the right of access or use it to harass the tenant.
(2) The landlord may enter the dwelling unit or premises:
(a) In case of emergency;
(b) When the tenant consents to the particular entry;
(c) To inspect the premises, make necessary or agreed repairs, alterations or improvements, supply agreed services, or exhibit the dwelling unit to prospective tenants, purchasers, mortgagees, workmen, contractors, or real estate agents: providing that the landlord shall give the tenant at least 2 DAYS' prior notice of the landlord's intent to enter and entry shall occur only at reasonable times during normal business hours, unless the tenant otherwise agrees;
(d) When the tenant has abandoned or surrendered the premises;
(e) Pursuant to court order;
(f) For a fire official of a fire department to inspect the premises for fire safety;
(g) For a code enforcement official to inspect the premises for code violations.
(3) Notice under (c): The landlord shall give a minimum 2 days written notice (may be oral if tenant explicitly agrees). The tenant may not unreasonably withhold consent to entry.
(4) The landlord has no other right of access except as stated in this section.

jurisdictions.habitability_section:
RCW 59.18.060. LANDLORD DUTIES (Habitability).
The landlord shall:
(1) Comply with applicable building, housing, and health codes, especially when conditions endanger or impair the health or safety of the tenant;
(2) Maintain structural components in good repair (roof, floors, walls, chimneys, foundations, etc.);
(3) Maintain shared/common areas in clean, sanitary condition and free from fire/accident hazards;
(4) Provide reasonable pest control at commencement of tenancy; maintain pest control for multi-unit buildings during tenancy (unless tenant caused infestation);
(5) Make necessary repairs to maintain the premises in the condition required at commencement, excluding normal wear and tear;
(6) Provide adequate locks and keys;
(7) Maintain master keys with reasonable care;
(8) Maintain all electrical, plumbing, heating, and other facilities in good working order;
(9) Maintain the unit in reasonably weathertight condition;
(10) Provide adequate garbage receptacles and arrange removal (except single-family homes);
(11) Supply adequate heat, water, and hot water at all times; [2023 AMENDMENT: On days of declared extreme heat warnings, landlord may not shut off electricity or water services for nonpayment; must immediately restore if cut off; tenant may enter payment plan not exceeding 6% of monthly income];
(12) Provide written fire safety disclosures (smoke detectors, sprinklers, fire alarms, smoking policy, emergency evacuation plans);
(13) Provide mold information and health hazards disclosure to tenant.

Repair timelines (RCW 59.18.070): After tenant's written notice of deficiency:
- Endangers health or safety (e.g., no heat, no hot water, dangerous electrical): repair within 24 HOURS;
- Refrigerator, stove, major plumbing failures: repair within 72 HOURS;
- Other deficiencies: repair within 10 DAYS.
